'''''Blyth v. Company Proprietors of the Birmingham Water Works''''' 1856, 11 Ex. Ch. 781 is a famous case in  concerning reasonableness in the law of .
The defendants were the  for the neighbourhood of . They had installed a fireplug into the hydrant near Mr. Blyth's house. That winter, during a severe frost, the plug failed causing a flood and damage to Mr Blyth's house. Blyth sued the Water Works for negligence.
In establishing the basis of the case, , made what has become a famous definition of negligence:
<blockquote>"Negligence is the omission to do something which a reasonable man, guided upon those considerations which ordinarily regulate the conduct of human affairs, would do, or doing something which a prudent and reasonable man would not do."</blockquote>
The court found that the severe frost could not have been in the contemplation of the Water Works. They can only be negligent if they fail to do what a  would do in the circumstances. Birmingham had not seen such cold in such a long time, and it would be unreasonable for the Water Works to anticipate such a rare occurrence.